# DeepAgents Streaming

Deep agents build on LangGraph's streaming infrastructure with first-class support for subagent streams. Use `agent.stream()` instead of `agent.invoke()` to receive real-time updates — LLM tokens, step progress, tool calls, and custom events.

## Basic usage

```typescript
for await (const [namespace, chunk] of await agent.stream(
  { messages: [{ role: "user", content: "Hello" }] },
  { streamMode: "updates", subgraphs: true },
)) {
  // namespace identifies the source agent
  // chunk contains the event data
}
```

The `subgraphs: true` option is required to receive events from subagents spawned via the `task` tool.

## Stream modes

| Mode | Tuple shape | What it streams |
|---|---|---|
| `"updates"` | `[namespace, chunk]` | Step completions — one event per node execution |
| `"messages"` | `[namespace, [message]]` | Individual LLM tokens and tool call chunks |
| `"custom"` | `[namespace, data]` | User-defined events emitted via `config.writer` |

### Combined modes

Pass an array to receive multiple modes in a single loop. The tuple gains a `mode` discriminator:

```typescript
for await (const [namespace, mode, data] of await agent.stream(
  { messages },
  { streamMode: ["updates", "messages"], subgraphs: true },
)) {
  if (mode === "updates") { /* step data */ }
  else if (mode === "messages") { /* token data */ }
}
```

## Namespaces

Each event includes a namespace (string array) that identifies which agent produced it.

| Namespace | Source |
|---|---|
| `[]` (empty) | Main agent |
| `["tools:abc123"]` | Subagent spawned by tool call `abc123` |
| `["tools:abc123", "model_request:def456"]` | Model request node inside a subagent |

### Resolving the source

```typescript
function resolveSource(namespace: string[]): { label: string; isSubagent: boolean } {
  const toolSegment = namespace.find((s) => s.startsWith("tools:"));
  if (toolSegment) {
    return { label: `subagent:${toolSegment.split(":")[1]}`, isSubagent: true };
  }
  return { label: "main", isSubagent: false };
}
```

## Token streaming (messages mode)

Use `message.text` for incremental token output. Use `AIMessageChunk.isInstance()` and `ToolMessage.isInstance()` to distinguish message types:

```typescript
import { AIMessageChunk, ToolMessage } from "langchain";

const [message] = data;

// Tool call chunks (streaming tool invocations)
if (AIMessageChunk.isInstance(message) && message.tool_call_chunks?.length) {
  for (const tc of message.tool_call_chunks) {
    if (tc.name) console.log(`Tool call: ${tc.name}`);
  }
}

// Tool results
if (ToolMessage.isInstance(message)) {
  console.log(`Tool result [${message.name}]: ${message.text?.slice(0, 150)}`);
}

// Regular AI content
if (message.text && !message.tool_call_chunks?.length) {
  process.stdout.write(message.text);
}
```

## Custom events (config.writer)

Tools can emit progress events using `config.writer`:

```typescript
const myTool = tool(
  async ({ topic }: { topic: string }, config: ToolRuntime) => {
    config.writer?.({ status: "starting", progress: 0 });
    // ... work ...
    config.writer?.({ status: "complete", progress: 100 });
    return result;
  },
  { name: "my_tool", description: "...", schema: z.object({ topic: z.string() }) },
);
```

Consume custom events with `streamMode: "custom"` (or include `"custom"` in the combined modes array).

## Interesting nodes for updates mode

When filtering `updates` mode events, the meaningful node names are `model_request` and `tools`. Other nodes are internal middleware steps that are typically not worth displaying.

## Subagent lifecycle pattern

Track subagent start/run/complete by combining namespace inspection with `updates` mode:

1. **Pending** — main agent's `model_request` contains a `task` tool call (check `msg.tool_calls`)
2. **Running** — events arrive from a `tools:*` namespace
3. **Complete** — main agent's `tools` node returns a `ToolMessage` with the subagent result
